As Jack wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/22/2004 at 01:27:40 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Three different cars are available to take five women and a man on 
a 
>particular journey. In how many different ways can the six people 
be 
>allocated to the cars so that the man is alone?


You can choose the car to carry the man in C(3,1) = 3 ways.

The 5 women can be allocated to 2 different cars in

       2^5 = 32 ways

Total arrangements =  3 x 32

                   =  96

>
>[Difficulty]
>Understanding the question
